Segfaults occurred while processing a BSON string and copying the byte sequence from the BSON buffer into a {{char*}} using PHP's {{ZVAL_STRINGL}} macro, which in turn utilizes {{_estrndup()}} and {{memcpy()}}. These were caused by the driver encountering {{0}} as the int32 length prefix of a BSON string. According to the [spec|http://bsonspec.org/#/specification], this length should include the null byte of the string, so we'd expect it to at least be {{1}} for an empty string. The driver does have a bug when checking for an invalid length in [line 912 of bson.c|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-php-driver/blob/1.3.7/bson.c#L912]. The {{INVALID_STRING_LEN}} macro is defined in [line 45 of bson.h|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-php-driver/blob/1.3.7/bson.h#L45]:

{code}
#define INVALID_STRING_LEN(len) (len < 0 || len > (64*1024*1024))
{code}

If {{len}} is {{0}}, this will fail to consider it invalid and the driver will *not* throw an exception and instead proceed to copy {{(len - 1)}} bytes from the buffer, attempting to omit the null byte:

{code}
if (INVALID_STRING_LEN(len)) {
    zval_ptr_dtor(&value);
    zend_throw_exception_ex(mongo_ce_CursorException, 0 TSRMLS_CC, "invalid string length for key \"%s\": %d", name, len);
    return 0;
}
buf += INT_32;

ZVAL_STRINGL(value, buf, len-1, 1);
buf += len;
{code}

Ultimately, this results in a very large unsigned integer being passed to {{memcpy()}} and causes a segfault.

At a glance, I believe BSON decoding of code (with and without scopes) and the deprecated DB pointer type may also be affected.

