See previous discussion in [PHP-949|https://jira.mongodb.org/browse/PHP-949?focusedCommentId=473549&page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.issuetabpanels:comment-tabpanel#comment-473549]. We check the generated name against the {{MAX_INDEX_NAME_LEN}}, which is 127. According to the [documentation|http://docs.mongodb.org/manual/reference/method/db.collection.ensureIndex/]:

{quote}
Index names, including their full namespace (i.e. database.collection) cannot be longer than 128 characters. See the getIndexes() field name for the names of existing indexes.
{quote}

While we currently check if the index name (e.g. {{x_1}}) exceeds 127 bytes, we would need to check the full namespace (e.g. {{db.collection.$x_1}}), which means deducting the database and collections lengths and an additional three bytes for periods and the dollar sign.

*However*, the above rules only apply to the mmapv1 storage engine. We should not do any of this validation in the driver and simply allow the command to return an error if the name is too long.

The implementation of {{MongoGridFS::remove()}} performs a find query to collect {{_id}} fields of {{fs.files}} documents to be deleted. That query does not respect {{justOne}}, and will collect identifiers from all matching documents. It then finds all chunks related to those identifiers and deletes them. Finally, it issues a remove query on {{fs.files}} using the original criteria and options (including {{justOne}}). This results in file documents being left behind (rightfully so) without any chunks (not good at all).

Solution would be to limit that initial find to a single document if {{justOne}} is {{true}}. Additionally, the final removal should delete based on the {{_id}} fields we've collected. Using the original criteria after we've deleted the correct chunks means that the final {{fs.files}} remove could possibly match a different document. That would leave us with two bad things: a file with no chunks and a missing file with orphan chunks.

----

